{"page_content": "Making an MVP     215\nWe can always set the x-axis range to 1\u20135 for both graphs, but this will not help our actual \nproblem. Instead, we can leave both of the graphs but also calculate whether, on average, \nwe rate books higher or lower than the Goodreads average. The following code block will \ncalculate this and add it underneath the average Goodreads rating graph:\nFig_avg_rating = px.histogram(books_rated, x='Average Rating', \ntitle='Average Goodreads Rating')\nst.plotly_chart(fig_avg_rating)\nimport numpy as np\navg_difference = np.round(np.mean(books_rated['My Rating'] \u2013 \nbooks_rated['Average Rating']), 2)\nif avg_difference >= 0:\n     sign = 'higher'\nelse:\n     sign = 'lower'\nst.write(f\"You rate books {sign} than the average Goodreads \nuser by {abs(avg_difference)}!\")\nThis code block makes our average and creates a dynamic string that will either say that \nthe Goodreads user rates books higher or lower than the average Goodreads user. The \nresult for my data is as follows:\nFigure 10.12 \u2013 Adding an average difference", "metadata": {"producer": "Adobe PDF Library 15.0", "creator": "Adobe InDesign 16.2 (Windows)", "creationdate": "2021-07-15T14:56:52+05:30", "source": "D:\\Users\\wpoga\\Documents\\Ebooks\\Artificial Intelligence\\Getting Started with Streamlit for Data Science Create and deploy Streamlit web applications from scratch in Python by Tyler Richards.pdf", "file_path": "D:\\Users\\wpoga\\Documents\\Ebooks\\Artificial Intelligence\\Getting Started with Streamlit for Data Science Create and deploy Streamlit web applications from scratch in Python by Tyler Richards.pdf", "total_pages": 282, "format": "PDF 1.6", "title": "", "author": "", "subject": "", "keywords": "", "moddate": "2021-07-15T17:57:51+05:30", "trapped": "", "modDate": "D:20210715175751+05'30'", "creationDate": "D:20210715145652+05'30'", "page": 231}, "type": "Document"}
